1. # Git Fundamentals (Local Environment)# 
Focus on setting up a local environment and understanding the core cycle of tracking changes.

## Initialize a Repository ##
* Create a new project folder: mkdir backend-journey && cd backend-journey.
* Start tracking: git init

## README & Learning Goals:##
Create a README.md file (touch README.md) to document your project's purpose and your specific learning objectives.

## Conventional Commits:
* Practice making "atomic" commits (one logical change at a time). Use the format: <type>: <description> (e.g., feat: add login logic or docs: update README).

* Branch Management: Use git checkout -b <branch-name> to create new branches for specific features or experiments, keeping your main branch stable. 

2. # GitHub Workflow (Cloud Integration)
Move your local work to the cloud and practice the standard industry workflow.
### * Backend-Journey Repo: Create a new repository on GitHub.
### * Link Local to Remote: git remote add origin <url>.
### * The .gitignore File: Create a .gitignore file to prevent tracking sensitive or unnecessary files (e.g., node_modules, .env, .DS_Store).

### * Pull Request (PR) Workflow:
### * Push feature branch: git push -u origin <feature-branch>.
### * Open a Pull Request to merge it into main on GitHub.
### * Review your own code/changes before merging. 

3. # Collaboration Practice
Simulate working on a team or contributing to the open-source community.

##  Forking: 
Find an interesting repository on GitHub and click "Fork" to create your own copy.

## Improvements: 
Clone your fork (git clone <your-fork-url>), make a meaningful improvement (e.g., fix a typo, add a comment), and push it to your fork.

## Contribution: 
Submit a Pull Request from your fork back to the original repository ("upstream").

## Exploration: 
Use GitHub's file browser to study how experienced developers structure their folders and name their variables. 

4. # Git Challenge (Advanced Troubleshooting)
Master advanced troubleshooting and history navigation tools.

## Resolve Merge Conflicts: 
Intentionally modify the same line of code on two different branches and merge them to practice manually picking the correct version.

## * Tools: git status to find conflicts, git diff to view differences, and manual editing to remove <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>> markers.

## Explore History:
git log --oneline: View a simplified history of all commits.
## git diff: Compare changes between your working directory and the last commit.

## git blame <file>: See exactly who changed which line and when.

## Undo Changes:
## git revert <hash>: Create a new commit that undoes the changes of a previous one (safe for shared history).
## git reset --hard <hash>
